## Edit 5 — Add the `‹ ›` guided-inquiry pager (ONLY if missing)

Goal: give the student free back/forward navigation across the inquiry cards.

**FIRST check if it already exists.** If the file already contains
`id="inq-prev"` AND `id="inq-pager-next"`, the pager is already present —
**skip Edit 5 entirely** (do NOT duplicate it). Otherwise apply all four parts
below. The reference is byte-identical to the already-shipped sims (e.g.
`L02-s1-inner-product-shell.html`) — copy exactly.

### 5a — CSS (add to the SIM's `<style>`, next to the existing `.inq-nav` rule)
Find the existing `.inq-nav{…}` rule. Ensure it has `justify-content:space-between`
(it already should), then add the two pager rules right after it:

```css
.inq-pager{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:8px;}
.inq-pager-btn{min-width:36px;padding:6px 11px;justify-content:center;font-size:13px;line-height:1;}
```
Also confirm `#inq-next` has `margin-left:auto;` so it stays pinned to the right
(the reference rule is `#inq-next{min-width:96px;justify-content:center;margin-left:auto;}`).
Do not touch `.inq-dots`, `.inq-step`, or any other inquiry CSS.

### 5b — Markup (wrap the pager buttons inside the existing `.inq-nav`)
The current nav usually looks like:
```html
<div class="inq-nav">
  <button id="inq-next" class="shell-btn primary">Next →</button>
</div>
```
Change it to (add the `.inq-pager` group BEFORE `#inq-next`; leave `#inq-next`
exactly as-is):
```html
<div class="inq-nav">
  <div class="inq-pager">
    <button id="inq-prev" class="shell-btn primary inq-pager-btn" title="Previous step" aria-label="Previous step" disabled>&lt;</button>
    <button id="inq-pager-next" class="shell-btn primary inq-pager-btn" title="Next step" aria-label="Next step">&gt;</button>
  </div>
  <button id="inq-next" class="shell-btn primary">Next →</button>
</div>
```

### 5c — Runtime: pager helpers + one call inside `inqShow` (inside the `Shell` IIFE)
Next to `inqShow`/`inqCards`, add the pager-state updater and the two navigation
functions (all use only in-scope `inqStep`, `inqCards`, `inqShow`):
```js
function inqUpdatePager(){
  const cards=inqCards();
  const prev=document.getElementById('inq-prev');
  const pnext=document.getElementById('inq-pager-next');
  if(prev) prev.disabled = inqStep<=0;
  if(pnext) pnext.disabled = inqStep>=cards.length-1;
}
function inqPrev(){
  if(inqStep>0) inqShow(inqStep-1);
}
function inqPagerNext(){
  const cards=inqCards();
  if(inqStep<cards.length-1) inqShow(inqStep+1);
}
```
Then, inside `inqShow(n)`, add a single call to `inqUpdatePager();` **immediately
before the existing `onStep(inqStep);` line** (so the arrows' disabled state tracks
the current card). Do NOT otherwise modify `inqShow` — leave the dots, the
`data-gate`/`Next`/`Finish` logic, and `onStep(inqStep)` untouched.

> **State preservation (do NOT deviate):** the pager buttons must call ONLY
> `inqShow(inqStep±1)`. Because `inqShow` already calls `onStep()`, the scene for
> the target card is restored identically to the `Next →` path. Do NOT add
> `onReset()`, do NOT clear `data-ready`, and do NOT wipe student answers on pager
> navigation — going back then forward must land on the same state.

### 5d — Wiring (in `wire()`, next to the `inq-next` listener)
After the existing `inq-next` listener, add:
```js
const inqPrevBtn=document.getElementById('inq-prev');
if(inqPrevBtn) inqPrevBtn.addEventListener('click',inqPrev);
const inqPagerNextBtn=document.getElementById('inq-pager-next');
if(inqPagerNextBtn) inqPagerNextBtn.addEventListener('click',inqPagerNext);
```

**Note on gating vs. the pager:** the main `Next →` button stays gated on
`data-gate` cards (unchanged). The `‹ ›` pager is deliberately free navigation
(review-friendly) — this matches the shipped reference. Do not add gating to the
pager unless explicitly asked.

